#Text=West Antarctica
#Text=West Antarctica
#Text=is the region of Antarctica that falls in the Western Hemisphere .
#Text=Regions
#Text=There are many regions of Antarctica , some of which are mountains and some of which are flatter areas .
#Text=However , these regions do not have their own articles because they offer few points of interest , let alone places to eat and sleep .
#Text=Ross Dependency
#Text=is the portion of Antarctica claimed by New Zealand .
#Text=Home to the largest Antarctic research station , McMurdo Station , and the world 's southernmost active volcano , Mount Erebus .
#Text=Marie
#Text=Byrd Land
#Text=is the largest area in the world that is n't claimed by any country .
#Text=This area is very empty even by Antarctic standards .
#Text=Chilean Antarctic Territory
#Text=contains the entire Antarctic Peninsula and overlaps with Queen Elizabeth Land and Argentine Antarctica .
#Text=It contains the Union Glacier Camp , which is a stopping point for most trips to the South Pole .
#Text=Queen Elizabeth Land
#Text=is the U.K. ' s claim to Antarctica .
#Text=It also contains the entire Antarctic Peninsula and overlaps with the Chilean Antarctic Territory and Argentine Antarctica .
#Text=Argentine Antarctica
#Text=is another Antarctic claim that overlaps with the Chilean Antarctic Territory and Queen Elizabeth Land .
#Text=Coats Land
#Text=is closer to the Antarctic Peninsula than Marie Byrd Land .
#Text=Ellsworth Land
#Text=is close to Vinson Massif .
#Text=Bases
#Text=( Excluding bases in the Antarctic Peninsula region )
#Text=( Argentina )
#Text=The world 's southernmost research station built on solid rock ( not on ice ) and is home to the world 's southernmost church .
#Text=( U.K. ) A research station that had been rebuilt 5 times and consists of 8 stringed modules .
#Text=There are retractable gigantic skis on the bottom of the station , allowing it to be moved .
#Text=( Germany ) A German research station on the Ekström Ice Shelf .
#Text=( South Africa ) A South African research station consisting of 3 double-storied modules .
#Text=Other destinations
#Text=is home to Antarctica 's highest point , Vinson Massif , at 4,892 m ( 16,050 ft ) .
#Text=is part of the Transantarctic Mountains .
#Text=An aircraft fueling station for planes flying between the Union Glacier Camp and the Amundsen-Scott South Pole Station is nearby .
#Text=is a long range of mountains and is part of the Transantarctic Mountains .
#Text=is another part of the Transantarctic Mountains .
#Text=is also part of the Transantarctic Mountains and is in Marie Byrd Land .
#Text=Understand
#Text=The mainland of Antarctica is divided into two sides : the east and the west .

#Text=While the Peninsula section of Antarctica is in the western portion of the continent , the Peninsula is not considered to be part of West Antarctica because it 's a more popular tourist destination and has a climate not quite as extreme due to its location off the Antarctic Plateau , which East and West Antarctica sit on .
#Text=West Antarctica is the emptiest region of Antarctica , as there are only 4 permanent research stations here , compared to 17 in East Antarctica .
#Text=Weather
#Text=Due to West Antarctica 's location on the Antarctic Plateau , most of this region lies at a high elevation , with ice miles deep .
#Text=This means that what would already be a very cold area if it was at a low elevation is even colder .
#Text=The high altitude , of course , brings health-related problems as well .
#Text=Landscape
#Text=West Antarctica is mostly on the Antarctic Plateau , and the Transantarctic Mountains is mostly in West Antarctica .
#Text=West Antarctica has a high altitude , which gets even higher when getting closer to the Transantarctic Mountains .
#Text=However , the terrain is generally flat on most parts of the Antarctic Plateau .
#Text=Get in
#Text=This region is extremely difficult to get into , like East Antarctica .
#Text=Unlike the Peninsula to the north , expedition ships generally avoid going to West Antarctica ; the only exception to this would probably be the Ross Sea .
#Text=However , a blue ice runway exists on Union Glacier Camp .
#Text=This camp is privately owned and operated by Antarctic Logistics & Expeditions LLC ( ALE ) .
#Text=Chartered flights from Punta Arenas fly tourists to the camp and run trips to the interior of Antarctica including the South Pole , Vinson Massif and Hercules Inlet .
#Text=Get around
#Text=Like the rest of Antarctica , transportation within bases can be done on feet , and transportation out of bases should be done on skis and/or base transport .
#Text=See
#Text=Bentley Subglacial Trench
#Text=.
#Text=The lowest point in the world not covered by oceans at 2,555 m ( 8,382 ft ) , although it is covered by ice .
#Text=Mount Sidley
#Text=.
#Text=Antarctica 's highest volcano ( extinct ) , at a whopping 4,181 m ( 13,717 ft ) .
#Text=Do
#Text=Vinson Massif
#Text=.

#Text=The highest point in Antarctica , Vinson Massif ( Mount Vinson ) stands at 4,892 m ( 16,050 ft ) ; climbs can be arranged by international travel agencies such as RMI and Adventure Consultants for some tens of thousands of dollars ( US ) per person , and take at least 14 days round trip from Punta Arenas .
#Text=Aside from the weather and the absurd difficulties involved in transport there , the climb is supposed to be pretty easy , especially by " seven summits " standards .
#Text=RMI : $ 43,600
#Text=Adventure Consultants : $ 43,000 .
#Text=Mount Tyree
#Text=.
#Text=This is one of the second seven summits ; in other words , it 's the second highest mountain peak in Antarctica .
#Text=As of 2017 , only 15 people had climbed to the top of Mount Tyree , so there are probably no tours to Mount Tyree .
#Text=Antarctic Ice Marathon
#Text=, ✉ rd@icemarathon.com .
#Text=The annual Antarctic Ice Marathon is the start of the World Marathon Challenge ( 7 Marathons on 7 continents in 7 days ) .
#Text=Racers will run 2 laps starting at the Union Glacier Camp .
#Text=There is also a half-marathon option . $ 18900 for 2019 and 2020 .
#Text=Eat
#Text=Like anywhere else in Antarctica , food will be served in bases , and must be carried when outside bases .
#Text=Drink
#Text=At most places in West Antarctica , there is ice covering the ground , so those with the ability to melt ice should not worry about water .
#Text=Sleep
#Text=Unless someone at a base is willing for you to lodge , you will need to camp .
#Text=Some excursions use Union Glacier Camp , a privately owned camp , as a base for their tourists .
#Text=Stay safe
#Text=Like the rest of Antarctica , West Antarctica is extremely cold and medical care is very limited .
#Text=Medical insurances are strongly recommended and sometimes required .
